   "entity": "character:cartographer",
   "title": "Elias Wren, Cartographer",
   "body": "Elias Wren came ashore at the Stilt Light aboard the coastal survey's boat, chart cases in hand and ink already at his cuffs, hired to put the shoals on paper at last after generations of surveyors gave up on the work. He is curious to a fault, the sort of visitor who asks one question more than manners strictly allow, and somehow means every one of them kindly. He has a small habit, tapping the edge of a chart three times with one knuckle before he will trust a sounding written on it. His instruments are ones he trusts absolutely; what he makes of the figures the shoals have lately been giving him is, for now, entirely his own business."
  },
  {
   "entity": "character:keeper",
   "title": "The Keeper of the Stilt Light",
   "body": "Maren Voss is the third of her family to keep the Stilt Light, having taken up the post the way her mother and grandmother did before her: by inheritance, by habit, and by a ledger she reads more often than she lets on. She is economical with words, her hands weathered from rope and wick, and unhurried even in the shoals' long storm season. She has a private habit of counting the lamp's turns under her breath before she will call the wick properly trimmed. Visitors find her plainspoken and exact. What the ledger asks of her, and what she intends to give it, she has not yet said aloud to anyone \u2014 least of all a stranger just off the boat."
  },
  {
   "entity": "character:sleeper",
   "title": "What the Shoals Hide",
   "body": "Sailors who work the water off the Stilt Light tell of a shape beneath the waves too large for any sounding line, patient, they say, as the tide itself, and never seen whole by living eyes. Keepers who have held the light across three generations speak of it only sideways, in old ledger terms passed hand to hand, and no chart has ever fixed its edges. On still nights the iron stilts are said to hum faintly, as though something below has only shifted in its rest. Whether the thing is myth, memory, or the plain truth of deep water, no surveyor's instrument has yet resolved."
  },
  {
   "entity": "location:lighthouse",
   "title": "The Stilt Light",
   "body": "Raised on iron stilts above the outer shoals, the Stilt Light has warned ships off the reef for three generations of keepers, each trained to the same exacting rhythm: trim the wick, feed the lamp whale-oil by the cupful, hold the flame steady through whatever the season sends. Below, the post keeps a ledger of its own \u2014 terms, debts, and duties recorded keeper to keeper in a careful hand \u2014 though what exactly binds each Keeper to the work is a matter the coast prefers not to ask aloud. Sailors navigating the shoals watch for its light before anything else; what the light is truly meant to hold steady, they leave for the keepers themselves to know."
  }
 ]
